<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n56132d"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n56" href="#n56132d">N56 (VI.B.41)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n56all.htm#n56132d"> 132(d)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Vaughn, ~ <small>Blue</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="n56132d"><li>FW 609.02 </li><li><a href="../../flex/tc/lextc.htm#n56132d">2010</a> </li><li><a href="../../flex/tc/l39tc.htm#n56132d">1939</a> </li><li><ms href="#n56132d">MS BL 47488-90</ms> </li><li>JJA 63:153 <a name="tcd3" href="../../ff/fdra/tda.htm#tcd3">Usage</a> </li><li> <a href="../../flex/tc/tcd3.htm#n56132d">Draft: IV&sect;3.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">A few adjective nicknames of Celtic origin are so common in England that they may be included here. Such are the Welsh <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> <mark><i>Vaughan</i>, small</mark>, <font color="green">[&hellip;]</font> It is likely that both <i>Begg</i> and <mark><i>Moore</i></mark> owe something to the Gaelic adjectives for little and <mark>big</mark> as in the well-known names of <i>Callum Beg</i>, Edward Waverley&apos;s gillie, and <i>McCallum More</i>. The Gaelic <i>Begg</i> is cognate with the Welsh <mark><i>Vaughan</i></mark>. <small> Ernest Weekley, <a name="EWRN2" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#EWRN2"><cite title="source">The Romance of Names</cite></a> (1914) 216</small></blockquote> <mm class="note">Note: Joyce presumably had the sourcebook as well as the notebook to hand when revising IV:3.3, hence &lsquo;pettyvaughan&rsquo; (vaughan = small) and &lsquo;magnumoore&rsquo; (Moore = big), entered at the same time. </mm> </dd></dl>
